131
00:07:37,256 --> 00:07:38,577
It's a survival instinct, really.

132
00:07:39,538 --> 00:07:47,465
Seeing the orange line in the green field, or hearing the twigs snap in the dead of night,

133
00:07:50,056 --> 00:07:54,037
Or the smell of smoke in the air can alert you to danger in the environment, and it can

134
00:07:54,077 --> 00:07:56,818
often mean the difference between life and death noticing this contrast.

135
00:07:57,198 --> 00:07:57,758
It's a good thing.

136
00:07:57,798 --> 00:08:02,399
It's a built-in Spidey sense, and we use this attention to contrast all the time for survival.

137
00:08:03,739 --> 00:08:07,360
But we have a hard time not noticing contrast, so it's great to use for advertising your

138
00:08:07,400 --> 00:08:10,861
product, getting it to stand up off the shelf, getting somebody to pick it up and play it.

139
00:08:11,481 --> 00:08:16,183
But in print media, this contrast occurs all at once, but when somebody's picked up the

140
00:08:16,243 --> 00:08:19,123
game or is watching the movie, the rules of contrast change.

141
00:08:20,281 --> 00:08:24,482
In a narrative, audiences like to see characters undergo transformative change or have a change

142
00:08:24,522 --> 00:08:26,703
on the world around them over the course of the narrative.

143
00:08:27,423 --> 00:08:31,604
We love seeing characters get thrown into these unfamiliar situations, struggle to adapt

144
00:08:31,644 --> 00:08:33,565
and survive, and learn something in the process.

145
00:08:35,806 --> 00:08:39,827
Now when talking about contrast or change in a narrative, I like to think of it in terms

146
00:08:39,867 --> 00:08:40,427
of polarity.

147
00:08:40,547 --> 00:08:44,708
It's still about the difference between two things, but it takes that difference and applies

148
00:08:44,748 --> 00:08:46,309
it to a two-dimensional coordinate system.

149
00:08:46,989 --> 00:08:49,790
So we have positive and negative polarities, and these could be anything.

150
00:08:51,974 --> 00:08:53,695
Good versus evil is one we're all familiar with.

151
00:08:54,455 --> 00:08:56,576
Light side versus dark side is one of my favorites.

152
00:08:57,656 --> 00:09:00,637
But they don't have to fit the pattern of good and bad, or good and evil.

153
00:09:00,657 --> 00:09:01,658
They just have to be different.

154
00:09:02,038 --> 00:09:03,878
So up versus down, left versus right.

155
00:09:04,298 --> 00:09:05,019
These would all work too.

156
00:09:09,940 --> 00:09:14,462
Now visualizing contrast with a polarized system, it makes it easier to see the movement

157
00:09:14,522 --> 00:09:14,962
over time.

158
00:09:16,400 --> 00:09:20,484
Polarity creates conflict or struggle between two opposing forces, and it allows us to see

159
00:09:20,544 --> 00:09:24,248
not just that a character is changing, but that they're changing in a direction.

160
00:09:24,368 --> 00:09:27,671
So two are away from a certain state of being over the course of the narrative.

161
00:09:30,173 --> 00:09:33,116
And if we want to track this, we can kind of change our model a little bit and track

162
00:09:33,156 --> 00:09:35,238
this shifting between polarities over time.

163
00:09:36,920 --> 00:09:40,543
So as players in a game, we like to be the ones that are driving that change in our character

164
00:09:40,583 --> 00:09:41,384
or the world around us.

165
00:09:41,444 --> 00:09:45,647
We want to choose how to play, what side to align ourselves with, who lives and who dies.

166
00:09:45,687 --> 00:09:47,468
So we want to be the one that's driving that change.

167
00:09:49,710 --> 00:09:53,413
So polarities or contrast is an important part of all narratives because it allows us

168
00:09:53,433 --> 00:09:57,135
to create these characters with different personalities, beliefs, and values.

169
00:09:57,155 --> 00:10:00,318
And it's that difference between these characters that creates conflict.

170
00:10:00,358 --> 00:10:02,860
And that conflict motivates a need for change or action.

171
00:10:04,342 --> 00:10:07,424
So everyone's familiar with this scene if you've played Mass Effect 1, but this struggle

172
00:10:07,444 --> 00:10:10,886
