183
00:10:45,151 --> 00:10:46,672
Then he cut to a reaction of a man's face.

184
00:10:47,693 --> 00:10:49,014
He showed a child in a coffin.

185
00:10:50,056 --> 00:10:50,856
And showed the man's face.

186
00:10:52,217 --> 00:10:55,581
They showed a woman laying seductively on the couch and then he cut back to the man's face.

187
00:10:56,181 --> 00:11:02,048
Now the audience who watched this experiment or this piece of film were asked to comment on the actor's performance.

188
00:11:02,429 --> 00:11:03,770
And they loved it. They raved about it.

189
00:11:04,131 --> 00:11:06,934
What a brilliant performance. Subtly magnificent.

190
00:11:07,375 --> 00:11:09,958
You could see the hunger when he saw that bowl of soup.

191
00:11:10,754 --> 00:11:13,555
Oh, his sadness, that sadness when he saw that child in the coffin.

192
00:11:13,575 --> 00:11:16,156
And oh, that lust in his eyes when he saw that woman.

193
00:11:16,656 --> 00:11:20,057
But really, it was the same expressionless face, the guy, every single time.

194
00:11:20,398 --> 00:11:24,479
So this just shows us that the audience perception of the actor's performance

195
00:11:24,519 --> 00:11:27,561
and what it meant was heavily influenced by the surrounding content.

196
00:11:28,861 --> 00:11:32,023
So the Kuleshov experiment demonstrated that the context of an experience

197
00:11:32,123 --> 00:11:35,264
can often hold more meaning than the content of an experience.

198
00:11:36,787 --> 00:11:38,847
So it was a bit hard to see in the previous example,

