00:26:48,926 --> 00:26:52,408
We've spread war across the galaxy before, and the genophage was the result, so

474
00:26:53,109 --> 00:26:56,311
we need to learn from the mistakes of our ancestors, or be doomed to repeat them.

475
00:26:58,384 --> 00:27:04,186
Okay, awesome! Maybe all these Krogan need is a strong female Krogan, uh, keep them in line, keep them in order, unite them as a group.

476
00:27:04,606 --> 00:27:09,168
So, I could see how this could work, maybe, uh, maybe helping them out's not such a bad idea after all.

477
00:27:10,228 --> 00:27:13,029
But Reeve's not buying it, so he's still determined to get revenge.

478
00:27:13,569 --> 00:27:17,451
You step outside and look around you and you see how destroyed the world is,

479
00:27:17,791 --> 00:27:21,692
how the Krogans grew tired of a peaceful life and started nuclear wars with each other,

480
00:27:21,772 --> 00:27:24,913
destroying their world long before the Solarians implemented the Genophage.

481
00:27:26,914 --> 00:27:27,554
Uh, okay, hmm.

482
00:27:30,572 --> 00:27:34,774
But then we also show the player that Krogan's were once a peaceful and advanced society.

483
00:27:34,814 --> 00:27:36,275
They weren't always creatures of war.

484
00:27:36,735 --> 00:27:38,256
And you can see this in their architecture.

485
00:27:41,718 --> 00:27:42,218
And their art.

486
00:27:42,518 --> 00:27:46,180
So there's a sense of wonder here, a sense of history, and you can imagine how things

487
00:27:46,240 --> 00:27:47,981
were long ago and might be again.

488
00:27:48,621 --> 00:27:53,184
So I'm going to stop spoiling this for you, but there's a lot more I won't spoil.

489
00:27:53,324 --> 00:27:57,886
But you can see how we expose the player to both sides of a polarized issue before making

490
00:27:57,926 --> 00:27:58,366
them choose.

491
00:27:59,597 --> 00:28:02,178
how to align themselves. And these are tough choices.

492
00:28:04,599 --> 00:28:07,681
Eventually you've got to make a decision. You've seen how vengeful and vicious these

493
00:28:07,721 --> 00:28:12,363
Krogan can be, how they wage wars against each other, destroy their own world, but you've

494
00:28:12,383 --> 00:28:16,565
also seen how hard they fought for their future, what they had been and could be again, and

495
00:28:16,605 --> 00:28:20,707
how a strong female Krogan might just inspire them to a peaceful greatness once again.

496
00:28:24,106 --> 00:28:25,287
And so now you have a narrative map

497
00:28:25,307 --> 00:28:27,509
that you can use when working with the content teams.

498
00:28:27,909 --> 00:28:29,510
So you can start thinking about how

499
00:28:29,530 --> 00:28:31,592
you can use various content to support

500
00:28:31,632 --> 00:28:33,473
the different sides of these polarized issues.

501
00:28:38,277 --> 00:28:39,678
So moving on to creating the content.

502
00:28:40,439 --> 00:28:41,760
Once you've established the high level story

503
00:28:41,780 --> 00:28:43,902
theme and polarities, you want to create

504
00:28:43,942 --> 00:28:44,943
content that supports them.

505
00:28:45,703 --> 00:28:47,925
So this is all about creating the language with visuals

506
00:28:47,965 --> 00:28:50,087
and audio to develop unique identities

507
00:28:50,127 --> 00:28:51,328
for the different sides of the conflict.

508
00:28:52,250 --> 00:28:54,071
for the various people and the places you'll encounter

509
00:28:54,312 --> 00:28:55,112
over the course of the game.

510
00:28:55,552 --> 00:28:58,314
And you also want to think about how the visual or audio design

511
00:28:58,354 --> 00:28:59,835
can change over the course of the narrative.

512
00:29:02,597 --> 00:29:03,898
And provide feedback to the player

513
00:29:03,938 --> 00:29:06,059
about the state of the world and how it's reacting

514
00:29:06,079 --> 00:29:07,160
to your choices as a player.

515
00:29:10,742 --> 00:29:11,782
So now when I talk about content,

516
00:29:11,802 --> 00:29:14,984
I'm talking about the VO, the characters, level, animation,

517
00:29:15,044 --> 00:29:17,806
sound effects, music, visual effects, all this stuff.

518
00:29:17,826 --> 00:29:19,047
There's a lot of content that goes

519
00:29:19,087 --> 00:29:20,168
into creating the experience.

520
00:29:20,944 --> 00:29:23,205
So at this point, good communication is essential.

521
00:29:23,586 --> 00:29:26,107
This process can end up being a bit like a game of telephone,

522
00:29:26,147 --> 00:29:29,109
where from the story side, things are pretty clear.

523
00:29:29,169 --> 00:29:31,110
But once it goes out to the different content teams

524
00:29:31,410 --> 00:29:34,011
and it goes through their various pipelines and workflows,

525
00:29:34,912 --> 00:29:37,433
the message can get diluted or lost in translation.

526
00:29:37,713 --> 00:29:41,094
And it's often the case that when it comes out on the other side and we combine it together

527
00:29:41,114 --> 00:29:44,215
to create this experience, all these assets aren't telling the same story.

528
00:29:44,595 --> 00:29:50,457
So it might be that the tone of the music or the VO isn't right for the scene or a character's

529
00:29:50,477 --> 00:29:53,738
appearance doesn't accurately reflect their personality.

530
00:29:54,578 --> 00:29:56,498
And when it doesn't work, it's really obvious.

531
00:29:57,839 --> 00:29:59,039
Here's a great example from...

532
00:30:00,090 --> 00:30:01,811
Dragon Age 2 Legacy DLC.

533
00:30:02,171 --> 00:30:08,115
This character is Larius and he's an old Grey Warden commander who goes off to the deep

534
00:30:08,175 --> 00:30:10,737
roads on his calling to die fighting Darkspawn.

535
00:30:10,777 --> 00:30:14,479
Except he doesn't really die, he just gets corrupted enough that they leave him alone

536
00:30:14,539 --> 00:30:17,361
so he's left to wander around slowly losing his mind.

537
00:30:18,082 --> 00:30:19,262
Okay, okay, yeah, I got it, I got it.

538
00:30:19,823 --> 00:30:22,864
So we go off and somebody records the animation for him,

539
00:30:23,405 --> 00:30:25,226
somebody else records the VO for him,

540
00:30:25,886 --> 00:30:27,527
and the character team is working on his character.

541
00:30:27,547 --> 00:30:28,928
And it wasn't until we put it all together

542
00:30:28,968 --> 00:30:30,989
that we realized how wrong we were,

543
00:30:31,069 --> 00:30:33,030
how different our understanding of who this character was.

544
00:30:33,351 --> 00:30:35,972
So he's hobbling around like this spry young monkey,

545
00:30:36,613 --> 00:30:39,454
and he's talking like a weezy-geezer,

546
00:30:40,635 --> 00:30:42,496
and he looks like this nuclear fallout victim,

547
00:30:42,556 --> 00:30:44,537
and we put it all together and it was wrong,

548
00:30:44,597 --> 00:30:45,438
it was all wrong.

549
00:30:47,452 --> 00:30:50,775
So we ended up having to go and re-record the animations.

550
00:30:50,795 --> 00:30:51,676
We had to get new mocap.

551
00:30:51,696 --> 00:30:53,218
We had to go and re-record the VO.

552
00:30:53,258 --> 00:30:54,759
We had to tweak his character.

553
00:30:55,520 --> 00:30:57,723
And we ended up spending a lot of time and money

554
00:30:59,344 --> 00:31:00,365
to fix this problem.

555
00:31:00,465 --> 00:31:02,047
So what could we have done differently?

556
00:31:02,107 --> 00:31:03,469
How could we have done this better?

557
00:31:04,450 --> 00:31:06,031
Surely more documentation, right?

558
00:31:06,312 --> 00:31:08,314
More documentation's always the answer.

559
00:31:09,377 --> 00:31:15,825
wrong. So sometimes excessive documentation can be the problem. At Bioware, we are occasionally

560
00:31:15,845 --> 00:31:19,910
guilty of writing narrative overviews like George R. R. Martin wrote a choose your own

561
00:31:19,930 --> 00:31:26,018
adventure book. So I once made the mistake of printing these narrative overviews out.

562
00:31:26,038 --> 00:31:28,161
I've got a little time to do a bit of light reading, right?

563
00:31:29,689 --> 00:31:32,591
and the resulting stack of papers was absolutely overwhelming.

564
00:31:32,671 --> 00:31:33,791
And it's now that I realize that,

565
00:31:34,852 --> 00:31:35,853
maybe I have to read through this,

566
00:31:35,893 --> 00:31:37,894
but a lot of the content developers and creators

567
00:31:38,294 --> 00:31:40,236
aren't going to read through this massive stack of papers,

568
00:31:40,576 --> 00:31:43,158
so they're going to remain unaware of the central themes of the game.

569
00:31:43,958 --> 00:31:46,780
So instead, they'll kind of resort to creating content that's cool.

570
00:31:47,120 --> 00:31:48,501
And cool content is cool, right?

571
00:31:48,581 --> 00:31:52,424
But it doesn't necessarily support the theme of the game as well as it could.

572
00:31:54,588 --> 00:31:59,451
Now we could have avoided this whole catastrophe if we just spent five minutes and used contrast

573
00:31:59,471 --> 00:32:02,472
to talk about where the characters sat between these different polarities.

574
00:32:03,013 --> 00:32:06,895
The process is really about communication and making sure that everyone understands

575
00:32:07,115 --> 00:32:08,816
what something is and what something's not.

576
00:32:11,997 --> 00:32:13,558
Now we want everything to support the story.

577
00:32:13,918 --> 00:32:18,021
The teams responsible for telling the narrative, the audio, and the visuals, and the gameplay

578
00:32:18,061 --> 00:32:20,283
elements should all be telling the same story with their work.

579
00:32:20,644 --> 00:32:25,227
So communication is obviously key here and it's not just about communicating more information

580
00:32:25,327 --> 00:32:29,971
but about boiling that giant stack of papers down to easy to understand ideas.

581
00:32:30,683 --> 00:32:32,004
So the idea is to keep it simple, right?

582
00:32:32,864 --> 00:32:34,845
When communicating the story vision with the content teams,

583
00:32:34,865 --> 00:32:36,526
you want to be able to give them a clear idea

584
00:32:36,546 --> 00:32:38,807
of the polarities that you want to explore,

585
00:32:38,907 --> 00:32:40,928
and then let them decide how to support

586
00:32:40,968 --> 00:32:43,009
those narrative polarities with polarities

587
00:32:43,049 --> 00:32:44,690
within their own disciplines.

588
00:32:51,713 --> 00:32:53,374
So artists can use visual polarities

589
00:32:53,414 --> 00:32:54,515
to support the narrative themes.

590
00:32:55,338 --> 00:32:57,560
And this goes back to the basics of visual design.

591
00:32:58,321 --> 00:32:59,943
Does the villain dress in black?

592
00:32:59,983 --> 00:33:01,544
Does the good guy wear a white hat?

593
00:33:02,005 --> 00:33:03,987
So getting back to the basics, you

594
00:33:04,007 --> 00:33:05,088
want to be able to see a character

595
00:33:05,108 --> 00:33:08,352
and immediately know and have a good idea of what he represents,

596
00:33:08,392 --> 00:33:10,214
who they are, and what do they want.

597
00:33:12,216 --> 00:33:16,120
So familiarize yourself with the basic visual components.

598
00:33:17,229 --> 00:33:20,089
visual design and how they can be used to tell a story or convey emotion.

599
00:33:20,349 --> 00:33:25,211
So visual components like line, color, shape, space, movement, tone, rhythm.

600
00:33:25,671 --> 00:33:28,712
Think about what each side represents and how they can support narrative polarities.

601
00:33:30,793 --> 00:33:34,094
Now it's kind of meta here, but the opposite of contrast is affinity.

602
00:33:34,374 --> 00:33:38,175
So sometimes it's not about making things look different, but making different groups

603
00:33:38,255 --> 00:33:39,715
look like they belong together.

604
00:33:42,200 --> 00:33:45,762
So for example, we used color, shape, and patterns

605
00:33:45,782 --> 00:33:49,305
to make these different groups of Templars or Grey Wardens

606
00:33:49,345 --> 00:33:50,606
kind of look like they belong together.

607
00:33:51,807 --> 00:33:54,489
A great example is the Darkspawn in Dragon Age Origins.

608
00:33:54,509 --> 00:33:56,670
They all looked really cool, but they were all very different.

609
00:33:57,171 --> 00:33:58,932
They didn't really look like they belonged together.

610
00:33:59,452 --> 00:34:02,274
And we wanted them to seem like they should be together,

611
00:34:02,915 --> 00:34:03,495
like a family.

612
00:34:05,021 --> 00:34:10,646
So we used tone and color to make these guys look like they belong in a group.

613
00:34:11,527 --> 00:34:13,709
In Mass Effect 3, it's immediately clear who the bad guys are.

614
00:34:13,729 --> 00:34:18,172
If you see these little glowy blue dots and it's running at you, start shooting and get the hell out of there.

615
00:34:19,233 --> 00:34:25,839
Now, visual polarities are also great for showing character progression or for externalizing the interior qualities of a character.

616
00:34:26,480 --> 00:34:28,021
This is a great example for Mass Effect.

617
00:34:29,312 --> 00:34:32,293
So if Shepard plays as a thinking, sympathetic paragon,

618
00:34:32,553 --> 00:34:33,353
he looks more human.

619
00:34:33,753 --> 00:34:36,614
Whereas if he plays more renegade,

620
00:34:38,035 --> 00:34:40,675
thinking or not thinking, more logical and unfeeling,

621
00:34:40,876 --> 00:34:42,496
he starts to look more like a machine.

622
00:34:42,516 --> 00:34:43,677
His skin starts to split,

623
00:34:43,937 --> 00:34:45,317
revealing these cybernetics beneath.

624
00:34:45,717 --> 00:34:47,118
And this is great because it reflects

625
00:34:47,158 --> 00:34:51,279
that larger story theme of humanity versus reapers

626
00:34:51,339 --> 00:34:52,760
or humanity versus technology.

627
00:34:55,232 --> 00:34:56,632
And think about how color can tell a story.

628
00:34:56,692 --> 00:34:59,374
For example, the red in this scene could represent danger.

629
00:35:00,314 --> 00:35:03,075
Or think about how the polarities of light and dark can tell a story.

630
00:35:03,436 --> 00:35:05,537
In this case, transition from life to death.

631
00:35:06,917 --> 00:35:08,318
So the same thing with audio polarities.

632
00:35:08,758 --> 00:35:13,321
Think about the basic audio components, whether it's volume, pitch, speed, rhythm.

633
00:35:14,561 --> 00:35:17,843
So figure out what the polarities are and think about how they could be used to represent

634
00:35:17,883 --> 00:35:18,943
the different sides of the story.

635
00:35:20,018 --> 00:35:21,298
Things like, you know, all these.

636
00:35:21,438 --> 00:35:24,199
And in Dragon Age 2, we use the polarities

637
00:35:24,239 --> 00:35:26,839
of known versus unknown when doing the ambient sound design.

638
00:35:28,439 --> 00:35:29,619
So for example, we wanted Kirkwall

639
00:35:29,639 --> 00:35:30,360
to feel like your home.

640
00:35:30,380 --> 00:35:31,280
It's a familiar place.

641
00:35:31,300 --> 00:35:32,480
You spend a lot of time there.

642
00:35:32,500 --> 00:35:33,620
We want you to feel safe there.

643
00:35:33,740 --> 00:35:35,560
So the ambient sound design is full

644
00:35:35,600 --> 00:35:37,101
of real and familiar sounds.

645
00:35:37,341 --> 00:35:39,541
Kids playing, dogs barking, merchants shouting.

646
00:35:40,761 --> 00:35:42,962
But by contrast, when you venture outside of Kirkwall,

647
00:35:43,122 --> 00:35:45,642
the locations are full of unreal and otherworldly sounds.

648
00:35:45,702 --> 00:35:47,142
It's strange and unfamiliar.

649
00:35:47,182 --> 00:35:49,423
It creates this sense of danger in comparison.

650
00:35:51,865 --> 00:35:56,126
Same thing with the music, using rhythm and tone in the music to represent the different

651
00:35:56,146 --> 00:35:59,967
sides of a polarized conflict like the Templars versus the Mages in Dragon Age.

652
00:36:02,567 --> 00:36:05,988
The music changes as the player completes quests for the different sides.

653
00:36:06,548 --> 00:36:10,189
It has a mystical sound when pursuing these Mage-related quests and a more structured,

654
00:36:10,329 --> 00:36:13,250
ordered, militant sound when pursuing Templar-related quests.

655
00:36:15,430 --> 00:36:18,851
So I love working in cinematics because we get to take all this great, meaningful content

656
00:36:19,171 --> 00:36:21,492
and put it together, and then we add our own layer of meaning on top.

657
00:36:22,630 --> 00:36:26,413
The camera can tell a story too, and it's a powerful tool in creating an experience.

658
00:36:28,135 --> 00:36:32,118
So things like the camera angle, lens, shot composition, camera movement, these all tell

659
00:36:32,178 --> 00:36:32,578
a story.

660
00:36:32,938 --> 00:36:37,302
So again, it's important to understand what the different cinematic components are and

661
00:36:37,342 --> 00:36:40,144
how they can be used to create meaning or support the story that you're trying to tell.

662
00:36:43,086 --> 00:36:45,868
For example, the camera angle can make a character look weak and vulnerable.

663
00:36:48,371 --> 00:36:52,272
or powerful and oppressive. In this case, it again reflects the larger theme of humanity

664
00:36:52,312 --> 00:36:58,874
versus the reapers. Just tilting the camera can make a world seem chaotic and out of balance.

665
00:36:59,814 --> 00:37:07,416
A close-up is personal, while a long shot feels detached. And we can combine these elements

666
00:37:07,436 --> 00:37:12,197
to create more complex shots, more complex emotions. In this case, a feeling of detachment

667
00:37:12,217 --> 00:37:14,878
or distance from your character in this world that's out of balance.

668
00:37:17,623 --> 00:37:20,063
So we can also use spatial context to add meaning through,

669
00:37:20,083 --> 00:37:22,324
a lot of people call this environmental storytelling.

670
00:37:24,765 --> 00:37:25,265
So in Dragon Age 2,

671
00:37:25,465 --> 00:37:27,145
we wanted to give the followers their own space

672
00:37:27,745 --> 00:37:29,326
that can further reflect their personalities.

673
00:37:29,406 --> 00:37:30,866
For example, we've got Varric here

674
00:37:30,886 --> 00:37:31,986
and he's got books behind him.

675
00:37:32,006 --> 00:37:33,587
He's a storyteller and that reflects that.

676
00:37:34,267 --> 00:37:35,267
Him sitting in this chair,

677
00:37:35,587 --> 00:37:37,568
kind of mirrors him sitting in a chair,

678
00:37:37,608 --> 00:37:39,988
telling more stories in an interrogation room

679
00:37:40,008 --> 00:37:40,868
in the framing narrative.

680
00:37:42,935 --> 00:37:44,537
And this is fun, this is a lot of fun.

681
00:37:45,577 --> 00:37:49,721
It's a great example of working with your level artists to tell a story outside of dialogue.

682
00:37:50,061 --> 00:37:55,505
So Thane, for example, is this badass lizard assassin, and so we stick him in this assassin's

683
00:37:55,585 --> 00:37:58,888
aquarium with these fluorescent lights and guns everywhere.

684
00:38:02,171 --> 00:38:05,233
And the environment around the player can serve to remind them of the things they've

685
00:38:05,273 --> 00:38:07,315
done, the adventures and the quests that they've already gone through.

686
00:38:09,446 --> 00:38:15,491
So now that you've used contrast and context to create your story, to create content that

687
00:38:15,531 --> 00:38:18,853
supports that story in the narrative themes of your game, you can put them all together

688
00:38:18,893 --> 00:38:20,454
and everything's telling the same story, right?

689
00:38:22,236 --> 00:38:24,397
Well, when this works, it is absolutely amazing.

690
00:38:24,437 --> 00:38:29,261
There's a dream sequence in Mass Effect 3, and it's very emotionally powerful and it

691
00:38:29,281 --> 00:38:31,403
stuck with me for a long time after playing the game.

692
00:38:32,639 --> 00:38:36,822
And in contrast to the real world, this dream world is desaturated and foggy.

693
00:38:36,982 --> 00:38:38,964
Your movement is slow and heavy.

694
00:38:39,685 --> 00:38:41,986
The sounds are strange and the music is haunting.

695
00:38:42,747 --> 00:38:46,430
And it really stands out from the rest of the game because the narrative, the visuals,

696
00:38:46,911 --> 00:38:50,694
the audio and the cinematography are all working together to create this experience for the player.

697
00:38:53,102 --> 00:38:57,367
Now, we also use reflective context to further shape the player experience.

698
00:38:57,947 --> 00:39:01,351
We want your current experience to be shaped by your previous choices and actions.

699
00:39:02,032 --> 00:39:06,818
So this takes a player experience and makes it a personal experience.

700
00:39:07,118 --> 00:39:09,501
And that's how you take players and turn them into fans.

701
00:39:10,388 --> 00:39:13,290
So for example, your experience of the Genophage mission I described earlier,

702
00:39:13,310 --> 00:39:16,532
it could be completely different if you didn't kill Rex in Mass Effect 1.

703
00:39:17,232 --> 00:39:18,693
It's pretty hard not to kill Rex.

704
00:39:19,173 --> 00:39:22,476
And so if he's still alive, it means that you've pursued this relationship with him,

705
00:39:22,516 --> 00:39:24,057
you've got a strong relationship with him,

706
00:39:24,097 --> 00:39:27,979
you understand how he thinks, how he feels, a bit more about the Krogan history,

707
00:39:28,459 --> 00:39:29,720
and how he could potentially be a leader.

708
00:39:29,780 --> 00:39:32,642
So it definitely has an impact on that experience of that mission.

709
00:39:34,007 --> 00:39:38,589
So your previous actions also influence the choices that you have in future conversations.

710
00:39:39,050 --> 00:39:43,292
We've got thousands of choices in our games, and every one that you make opens up or closes

711
00:39:43,392 --> 00:39:44,713
off future choices.

712
00:39:45,534 --> 00:39:49,616
So some people occasionally lament the lack of choices, but not realizing that the choices

713
00:39:49,656 --> 00:39:53,739
available to them at any point in these Bioware games are based on how they've been playing

714
00:39:53,759 --> 00:39:54,459
the game so far.

715
00:39:55,159 --> 00:39:58,681
Now we want you also to see your choices reflected in the cinematics.

716
00:40:01,543 --> 00:40:02,324
And this is something that...

717
00:40:03,311 --> 00:40:05,114
we could have done a lot better in Dragon Age Origins.

718
00:40:05,955 --> 00:40:06,516
If you've played it,

719
00:40:07,037 --> 00:40:08,559
you might be familiar with the murder knife.

720
00:40:10,851 --> 00:40:14,994
Now, this was this kind of weird, wooden handle, dinky kitchen knife.

721
00:40:15,955 --> 00:40:21,439
And at various points throughout the game, you had this opportunity to kill various NPCs for whatever reason.

722
00:40:21,899 --> 00:40:29,744
And when you did so, I always wanted to kill them with this giant two-sided axe with purple electricity and flame shooting out that I've been carrying around for like 20 levels.

723
00:40:30,205 --> 00:40:36,609
But when I killed this guy, I kind of pulled this knife out from behind my back and you throw it or swing it or...

724
00:40:37,635 --> 00:40:41,536
We had all sorts of these scenes and it was really a missed opportunity to do something

725
00:40:41,596 --> 00:40:45,998
unique and show the player killing a guy in a way that was consistent with how he built

726
00:40:46,038 --> 00:40:47,978
his character and how he'd been playing the game so far.

727
00:40:48,739 --> 00:40:53,500
So for Dragon Age 2, this was really important to me to fix this and allow the player to

728
00:40:53,540 --> 00:40:57,502
kill somebody with their weapon in a way that was consistent with their character, how they'd

729
00:40:57,522 --> 00:40:58,442
been playing the game so far.

730
00:40:59,356 --> 00:41:01,776
So just as an example, you can definitely

731
00:41:01,816 --> 00:41:04,737
see the results in Dragon Age 2 and the Dragon Age 2 DLC.

732
00:41:04,777 --> 00:41:07,438
This is a few examples of a cinematic kill scene

733
00:41:07,458 --> 00:41:09,178
where you take out a boss in various ways,

734
00:41:09,218 --> 00:41:12,399
depending on whether you're an archer, a rogue, or a mage.

735
00:41:12,979 --> 00:41:14,839
So this creates a very personal experience

736
00:41:14,859 --> 00:41:16,819
for the player, which is much, much, much more satisfying.

737
00:41:18,820 --> 00:41:20,520
Now we also use temporal context to help

738
00:41:20,600 --> 00:41:21,640
shape the player experience.

739
00:41:22,120 --> 00:41:23,401
Now in BioWare games in particular,

740
00:41:23,481 --> 00:41:26,121
you have a lot of freedom in where you go, what you do,

741
00:41:26,221 --> 00:41:27,242
what order you do things in.

742
00:41:28,415 --> 00:41:31,738
So when working on any conversation or cut scenes, we have to be aware of, well, what

743
00:41:31,758 --> 00:41:32,739
has the player already done?

744
00:41:32,779 --> 00:41:34,120
What does he still have left to do?

745
00:41:34,180 --> 00:41:34,821
What does he know?

746
00:41:34,961 --> 00:41:36,483
What does he not know at any point in the game?

747
00:41:38,245 --> 00:41:39,586
And sometimes timing is important.

748
00:41:39,946 --> 00:41:43,590
In Mass Effect 2, if you don't go save your crew fast enough after they get kidnapped

749
00:41:43,610 --> 00:41:46,533
by the collectors, a lot of them die, including Kelly Chambers.

750
00:41:51,037 --> 00:41:52,118
Who's going to feed your fish now?

751
00:41:55,968 --> 00:42:00,991
So this is also important when creating the DLC for Dragon Age 2 because the player can

752
00:42:01,031 --> 00:42:03,452
play this DLC at any point in time in the main game.

753
00:42:03,472 --> 00:42:06,333
They can play in Act 1, Act 2, or Act 3 during the main playthrough.

754
00:42:07,193 --> 00:42:11,415
And a lot of consideration had to be given to what was a player's previous experiences

755
00:42:11,635 --> 00:42:13,256
and how could they shape the current experience.

756
00:42:14,136 --> 00:42:15,436
So just as an example.

757
00:42:16,887 --> 00:42:20,548
In the Dragon Age 2 DLC Legacy, Hawk learns a bit about the true nature of his father.

758
00:42:20,908 --> 00:42:24,369
And it was really important to us that Hawk be able to have this discussion with his mother

759
00:42:24,409 --> 00:42:25,710
to talk about what he had discovered.

760
00:42:26,390 --> 00:42:30,711
But depending on when you played this DLC in relation to the main game, Hawk's mother

761
00:42:30,751 --> 00:42:33,412
could be alive, missing, or dead.

762
00:42:33,592 --> 00:42:37,073
So we had to figure out how to make this scene in all these different cases.

763
00:42:38,015 --> 00:42:42,919
and make it meaningful. So in the case of Hawk's mother being dead, we set up the scene,

764
00:42:42,959 --> 00:42:47,183
we use these cinematic polarities to create this effect where it's really Hawk having

765
00:42:47,203 --> 00:42:51,828
this conversation with a memory of his mother. And this allows us to add more emotional weight

766
00:42:51,868 --> 00:42:57,413
to the scene. Now, occasionally players are able to play through your content in a way

767
00:42:57,433 --> 00:42:58,914
that you might not have expected.

768
00:42:59,927 --> 00:43:03,508
In Dragon Age Origins, the party camp was this safe place where you could go and equip

769
00:43:03,548 --> 00:43:07,069
your gear, chat with your followers, pursue romances, and it was a safe place.

770
00:43:07,109 --> 00:43:08,730
You never got attacked in the party camp.

771
00:43:09,650 --> 00:43:13,072
Except for that one time we thought it'd be cool to attack you in the player camp, right?

772
00:43:13,512 --> 00:43:17,514
So you get attacked, you take out these bad guys, and you're covered head to toe in blood.

773
00:43:17,674 --> 00:43:21,035
But you just kind of go back to business as usual, chatting with your followers, swapping

774
00:43:21,075 --> 00:43:23,136
gear, pursuing romantic relationships.

775
00:43:24,036 --> 00:43:26,517
And these romantic relationships, they take a lot of time.

776
00:43:27,863 --> 00:43:32,766
to get to, so we wanted these to be sweet and sensual, there's nice romantic music playing,

777
00:43:33,446 --> 00:43:38,809
but in this case, in this case you were covered in blood.

778
00:43:41,330 --> 00:43:46,592
So what was supposed to be this sweet romantic scene ends up just being disturbingly bizarre

779
00:43:46,632 --> 00:43:47,353
and hilarious.

780
00:43:49,042 --> 00:43:50,942
because of what the player had done previously.

781
00:43:50,982 --> 00:43:52,523
And this is not what we wanted.

782
00:43:52,543 --> 00:43:54,483
This isn't what I wanted when I created this scene.

783
00:43:54,523 --> 00:43:55,223
It was all wrong.

784
00:43:55,984 --> 00:43:59,064
So the lesson here is that when you craft these key moments

785
00:43:59,084 --> 00:44:01,625
in your game, just be aware of what the player might

786
00:44:01,665 --> 00:44:03,486
be able to do before and how it could potentially

787
00:44:03,766 --> 00:44:04,646
sabotage your efforts.

788
00:44:06,347 --> 00:44:08,107
So back to contrastive juxtaposition.

789
00:44:08,927 --> 00:44:11,268
So now that we've talked about contrast and context

790
00:44:11,308 --> 00:44:14,129
when creating your story, your content, and your cinematics,

791
00:44:14,509 --> 00:44:16,429
how do we use all these together to create

792
00:44:16,449 --> 00:44:17,050
these powerful?

793
00:44:18,137 --> 00:44:19,278
emotionally engaging scenes.

794
00:44:21,339 --> 00:44:24,120
So, first I'd like to give you kind of a simple example

795
00:44:24,641 --> 00:44:26,622
of contrastive juxtaposition in music.

796
00:44:27,322 --> 00:44:29,163
Now, normally I wouldn't suggest this

797
00:44:29,183 --> 00:44:30,424
when showing a clip from the show,

798
00:44:30,524 --> 00:44:32,445
but pay close attention to the dialogue,

799
00:44:32,905 --> 00:44:33,805
especially towards the end.

800
00:44:35,946 --> 00:44:37,207
♪ When you're in a fall ♪

801
00:44:39,908 --> 00:44:42,070
♪ If you can't fly ♪

802
00:44:48,471 --> 00:44:51,853
I'd better start rocking or I'll really give him something to cry about.

803
00:44:51,933 --> 00:44:57,276
Shut up, buddy. It's cool. Check it out. Check it out.

804
00:44:57,416 --> 00:44:58,596
Here it comes.

805
00:44:59,017 --> 00:45:01,098
Here it comes.

806
00:45:01,598 --> 00:45:02,418
Yes! Yes!

807
00:45:02,498 --> 00:45:05,220
Rawr! Yes! Yes! Yes!

808
00:45:05,280 --> 00:45:05,620
Rawr!

809
00:45:05,800 --> 00:45:06,401
Rawr!

810
00:45:06,621 --> 00:45:09,342
Rawr! Yes! Yes!

811
00:45:09,822 --> 00:45:11,103
Rawr!

812
00:45:11,743 --> 00:45:12,484
Rawr!

813
00:45:12,504 --> 00:45:13,564
This is pretty cool.

814
00:45:13,624 --> 00:45:14,245
Yes! Yes!

815
00:45:14,265 --> 00:45:15,906
Yeah! Yeah!

816
00:45:19,735 --> 00:45:21,337
What? What's going on?

817
00:45:21,837 --> 00:45:22,218
It's true.

818
00:45:22,438 --> 00:45:28,584
How come they don't just like play that cool part through the whole song?

819
00:45:28,644 --> 00:45:34,590
Well, Beavis, if they didn't have like a part of the song that sucked, then it's like the other part wouldn't be as cool.

820
00:45:34,870 --> 00:45:37,013
Really? You're pretty smart.

821
00:45:37,053 --> 00:45:38,894
You're a tough one, Beavis.

822
00:45:38,995 --> 00:45:39,535
Yes. Yes.

823
00:45:44,990 --> 00:45:48,112
So it's a pretty silly example, but I think you get the point I was trying to make.

824
00:45:48,612 --> 00:45:53,356
It demonstrates this basic concept of how the juxtaposition of these two contrasting elements,

825
00:45:53,696 --> 00:45:58,580
in this case, the soft verse and the hard chorus, can have an emotional impact on the viewers.

826
00:45:59,580 --> 00:46:02,883
And I love this idea that if they didn't have a part of the song that sucked,

827
00:46:03,423 --> 00:46:04,964
then maybe the other part wouldn't be as cool.

828
00:46:05,545 --> 00:46:07,726
Now, obviously, none of us want any part of our games to suck,

829
00:46:08,367 --> 00:46:11,829
but it just speaks to the fact that you can't necessarily crank it up to 11 and leave it.

830
00:46:13,748 --> 00:46:17,650
It's that back and forth between contrastive elements that grabs your attention and holds

831
00:46:17,670 --> 00:46:18,150
your attention.

832
00:46:18,590 --> 00:46:23,333
And sometimes you need that slow moment, that calm moment before the storm for your key

833
00:46:23,353 --> 00:46:24,513
moment to really stand out.

834
00:46:25,294 --> 00:46:29,776
So to do this, you have to first identify what those story moments are around that target

835
00:46:29,816 --> 00:46:30,056
moment.

836
00:46:30,997 --> 00:46:35,159
So the story moments in that example I showed at the very beginning is Shepard is helping

837
00:46:35,199 --> 00:46:36,180
Joker into the escape pod.

838
00:46:37,060 --> 00:46:42,143
She gets thrown back by an explosion, barely presses that eject button before another blast ... ... ...

839
00:46:43,009 --> 00:46:49,393
shoots her right out of the Normandy, the Normandy explodes, and then she floats off

840
00:46:49,453 --> 00:46:51,174
into space to die.

841
00:46:51,994 --> 00:46:55,516
So if these are the kind of story beats of your scene, what is the moment that you want

842
00:46:55,536 --> 00:46:56,397
to stand out?

843
00:46:56,437 --> 00:46:59,639
What is the moment you really want to have that emotional impact on the player?

844
00:47:00,379 --> 00:47:03,100
So in this case, it's Shepard floating away into space to die.

845
00:47:04,521 --> 00:47:07,063
So if that's your key moment, how do you make it stand out?

846
00:47:08,487 --> 00:47:11,009
And what you want to do is you want to make the lows lower

847
00:47:11,029 --> 00:47:11,809
and the highs higher.

848
00:47:11,869 --> 00:47:14,851
Create that strong contrast in the narrative, the audio,

849
00:47:14,891 --> 00:47:15,852
and the visuals around it.

850
00:47:17,553 --> 00:47:19,915
So in this case, we want to highlight this narrative shift

851
00:47:19,955 --> 00:47:20,915
from alive to dead.

852
00:47:22,116 --> 00:47:25,018
Then we do that by first showing this massive explosion,

853
00:47:25,038 --> 00:47:27,360
the biggest explosion you could have,

854
00:47:27,700 --> 00:47:30,582
and then immediately cutting to these tiny, tiny, tiny little

855
00:47:30,642 --> 00:47:31,602
VFX in the background.

856
00:47:32,203 --> 00:47:34,164
And you can kind of see how we might map out

857
00:47:34,184 --> 00:47:34,904
that polarity shift.

858
00:47:35,760 --> 00:47:39,643
Now, the music completely cuts out as soon as Shepard is outside of the Normandy, and

859
00:47:39,663 --> 00:47:44,787
the music doesn't come back until the sad piano at the end, and sad piano will always

860
00:47:44,847 --> 00:47:45,368
make you cry.

861
00:47:48,110 --> 00:47:52,133
So the sound design in the scene goes from sounds of the world around Shepard to just

862
00:47:52,193 --> 00:47:55,455
sounds of Shepard and her suit as she's gasping for air.

863
00:47:57,717 --> 00:48:03,502
In a single shot we go from a close-up to this wide shot, creating this feeling of loss

864
00:48:03,542 --> 00:48:04,903
of separation from your character.

865
00:48:06,315 --> 00:48:07,916
And here's that transition.

866
00:48:08,896 --> 00:48:13,339
And then in the final shot, we watch the sun set back behind the planet until the world

867
00:48:13,400 --> 00:48:13,780
is dark.

868
00:48:14,420 --> 00:48:18,423
And this visual clarity mirrors the narrative shift from life to death.

869
00:48:19,223 --> 00:48:21,865
So now that we've kind of gone over this, let's take another look at that scene and

870
00:48:21,965 --> 00:48:23,326
see how all these elements work together.

871
00:49:45,310 --> 00:49:47,551
So I hope I've given you a better understanding

872
00:49:47,591 --> 00:49:49,212
of these different shifts in polarity

873
00:49:49,752 --> 00:49:51,873
and why contrast and context are important

874
00:49:51,893 --> 00:49:53,174
and how we use them as creative tools

875
00:49:53,674 --> 00:49:55,655
throughout the development process when creating the story,

876
00:49:55,715 --> 00:49:58,396
the content, the cinematics, and the overall experience

877
00:49:58,416 --> 00:49:58,836
for the player.

878
00:49:59,537 --> 00:50:01,958
So some key takeaways here are identify your story themes

879
00:50:01,998 --> 00:50:04,219
early so you can inform design further down the line.

880
00:50:04,479 --> 00:50:06,480
Keep it really simple when communicating these ideas

881
00:50:06,500 --> 00:50:07,461
to your content teams.

882
00:50:07,981 --> 00:50:09,562
And remember that context can really

883
00:50:09,582 --> 00:50:12,783
have a significant impact on the meaning of an experience.

884
00:50:13,648 --> 00:50:16,249
If you're interested in learning more about narrative, visual,

885
00:50:16,289 --> 00:50:18,831
and audio polarities, I'd highly recommend these books.

886
00:50:19,371 --> 00:50:21,032
The Writer's Journey by Christopher Vogler,

887
00:50:21,252 --> 00:50:23,973
The Visual Story by Bruce Block, and Sound Design

888
00:50:24,013 --> 00:50:25,034
by David Sonenshine.

889
00:50:27,395 --> 00:50:28,296
So that's the end of my talk.

890
00:50:28,376 --> 00:50:29,677
I hope you have some time for questions.

891
00:50:29,877 --> 00:50:31,237
If I don't get your question today,

892
00:50:31,518 --> 00:50:33,679
please feel free to email me or follow me on Twitter.

893
00:50:34,239 --> 00:50:35,520
And I'd definitely be interested in hearing your feedback.

